// Extended Exercise 1 {Savings in Singapore}


**********************************************
webuse set http://www.ncer.edu.au/stata-resources/data/Honours/
webuse "savings.dta",clear

g dates	=	tq(1975q1)+_n-1
tsset dates, quarterly

// 1. Generate required variables
qui g dsav		=	(income-consump)-(L4.income-L4.consump)
qui g dincome	=	income-L4.income
qui g real		=	interest-100*log(price/L4.price)
qui g dreal		=	real-L4.real

// 2. Estimate using OLS
reg dsav dincome dreal

* check for autocorrelation
estat dwatson

* check coefficients against expectations.
* We expect savings to be positively correlated with income. b1 > 0.
* We expect savings to be positively correlated with interest. b2 >0.

* check statistics.
* R^2 and adjR^2  show above 80% of variation in savings is explained by the model.
* F statistic is highly significant
* DW test statistic indicates likely positive autocorrelation.

// 5. (a) Plot residuals
predict resid, residuals
scatter resid dates

*The scatter plot dips from 1985 to 1993(?).
*Have a look at fitted line against actual line
predict fitted, xb
twoway (tsline fitted) (tsline dsav)

// 5. (b) test normality of residuals
sktest resid
*sktest null hypothesis: variable is normal

// 5. (c) test second order autocorrelation (Breusch-Godfrey test)
estat bgodfrey, lags(2)
* H0: No autocorrelation
* Second order correlation - yes

// 5. (d) White's test for heteroskedasticity
imtest, white
* H0: homoskedastic
* Heteroskedastic - no


**********************************************


// Extended Exercise 2 {Demand for Money in Kenya}


**********************************************
webuse "kenya.dta", clear
//set time variable
rename obs dates
tsset dates, yearly

// Generate required variables
qui g lm2cpi		=	log(m2/cpi)
qui g dlm			=	D1.lm2cpi
qui g lngdpcpi		=	log(ngdp/cpi)
qui g dly			=	D1.lngdpcpi
qui g interestpc	=	interest/100
qui g di			=	D1.interestpc

// 1. Regress
reg dlm dly di

// 2. Check OLS assumptions
predict double resid,residuals
tsline resid

sktest resid			// Check normality

estat bgodfrey, lags(1)	// Check autocorrelation

imtest, white			//	Check heteroskedasticity

// 3. Other tests
test dly
test (dly=1) (di=0)


**********************************************


// Extended Exercise 3 {Inflation Hikes in Kenya}


**********************************************
// 1. Plot inflation
tsline inf

// 2. Estimate the inflation model
qui g growth	=	D1.lngdpcpi
qui g lerate	=	log(erate)
qui g erets		=	D1.lerate

reg inf growth erets

predict double e, residuals
tsline e

// 3. Estimate inflation model  with structural break
qui g dum = (1992<=dates & dates<=1994)		// This creates a dummy variable for 1992 < dates < 1994
reg inf growth erets dum

predict double e_dum,residuals
tsline e_dum

// Extended Exercise 4 {Threshold Model of US Growth}


**********************************************
webuse "thresh1.dta",clear

rename obs year
tsset year, yearly

// The "growth" and "inf" variables provided are incorrect.
// Drop wrong variables
drop growth inf

// Create required variables
qui g lyus = log(y_us)
qui g growth = 100*D1.lyus
qui g lpus = log(p_us)
qui g inf = 100*D1.lpus

// What is the value of k? First, identify appropriate value of k.
// Estimate the model using all feasible values for k (k=1,...,9), and use k that gives the lowest RSS.
g d1 = (inf>1)	// k=1
g d2 = (inf>2)	// k=2
g d3 = (inf>3)	// k=3
g d4 = (inf>4)	// k=4
g d5 = (inf>5)	// k=5
g d6 = (inf>6)	// k=6
g d7 = (inf>7)	// k=7
g d8 = (inf>8)	// k=8
g d9 = (inf>9)	// k=9

g dinf1 	= d1*	(inf-1)
g dinf2 	= d2*	(inf-2)
g dinf3 	= d3*	(inf-3)
g dinf4 	= d4*	(inf-4)
g dinf5 	= d5*	(inf-5)
g dinf6 	= d6*	(inf-6)
g dinf7 	= d7*	(inf-7)
g dinf8 	= d8*	(inf-8)
g dinf9		= d9*	(inf-9)

reg growth inf dinf1	// k=1
reg growth inf dinf2	// k=2
reg growth inf dinf3	// k=3
reg growth inf dinf4	// k=4
reg growth inf dinf5	// k=5
reg growth inf dinf6	// k=6
reg growth inf dinf7	// k=7
reg growth inf dinf8	// k=8
reg growth inf dinf9	// k=9

// The RSS from each of the estimated models correspond to the values in Table 1 in the question
// k=7 has the lowest RSS.
// The appropriate model is the one with k=7

// Exercise 1 {US Population Survey Data}

webuse "cpso8.dta", clear

// 1. Estimate the model
reg ahe female
* The coefficient of "female" is significant, therefore the wage differential is significant

// 2. Estimate model with additional factors
reg ahe female bachelor age
* The coefficient of "female" is still significant, and has increased in magnitude.
* The other factors are also significant.

// Exercise 2 {CAPM}

webuse "capm.dta", clear
qui g dates	=	tm(1998m1)+_n-1
tsset dates, monthly
* Note that the dates only go until December 2007, not December 2008

// Generate the market risk premium variable
g mrp	=	mkt - rkfree

// Generate firm risk premium
g msftpr	=	msft - rkfree
g gepr		=	ge - rkfree
g gmpr		=	gm - rkfree
g ibmpr		=	ibm - rkfree
g dispr		=	dis - rkfree
g xompr		=	xom - rkfree

// 1. Estimate the CAPM model for each firm
qui reg msftpr mrp		// Microsoft
est store msft		// -est- is an abbreviation of -estimates-
qui reg gepr mrp		// GE
est store ge
qui reg gmpr mrp		// GM
est store gm
qui reg ibmpr mrp		// IBM
est store ibm
qui reg dispr mrp		// Disney
est store dis
qui reg xompr mrp		// Exxon-Mobile
est store xom

// 2. Check intercept parameter
// Display estimates
est table msft ge gm ibm dis xom, star	title("CAPM Estimates")
			// The -star- option uses stars to denote significance levels.
			// See http://www.stata.com/manuals13/restimatestable.pdf
* None of the intercept parameters are significant, therefore finance theory holds

// 3. Microsoft
// (a)
qui reg msftpr mrp
predict pr_msftpr

tsline msftpr pr_msftpr

// (b)
test _b[mrp]=1
* p-value = 0.0241

// (c)
// Since the estimate for beta is larger than 1, the p-value for the one-sided test is simply half of the p-value in part (b)
* p-value = 0.0241/2

webuse "caschool.dta", clear

// 1. Draw scatterplot and regression line
twoway (scatter testscr avginc) (lfit testscr avginc)

// 2. Regress test scores on student teacher ratio
reg testscr str
* For every additional student per teacher, the test score is expected to decrease by 2.28
* This is rejected at p =0.001, p=0.01, p=0.05
* Adj R^2 is 0.05 so this model is not very good.
* Standard error of regression is SQRT(MSE) = 18.581

// 3. Regress test score on class size
// Generate class size variable and estimate regression equation
// It was assumed here that class size=total enrolment/teachers
g size = enrl_tot/teachers
reg testscr size
* The predicted average test score for a class of 22 students is
* score = 698.933 - 2.279808*22
di _b[_cons] + _b[size]*22

// 4. Sample average
mean size
mean testscr
* Note: The sample average of class size is computed here as 19.64, not 21.4 as stated in the task sheet.

// Exercise 4 {US Current Population Survey Data}


**********************************************
webuse "cpso8.dta", clear

// 1. Estimate model
reg ahe age

// (a)(b)
// The age coefficient is statistically significant, and the magnitude of the coefficient seems economically significant.
// However the model itself only explains 3% of the variation (R^2 = 0.03)

// (c) Construct confidence interval
di _b[age]	-	1.96 * _se[age]		// Lower limit of confidence interval
di _b[age]	+	1.96 * _se[age]		// Upper limit of confidence interval

// 2. Predict earnings
// 26 year old worker
di _b[_cons] + _b[age]*26
// 30 year old worker
di _b[_cons] + _b[age]*30

webuse "caschool.dta",clear
// 1. Run the regression
reg testscr str					// Model 1
est store model1

// 2. Regress Model 2
reg testscr str el_pct			// Model 2
* Coefficient of "str" was -2.279808. It is now -1.101296.
est store model2

// 3. Regress Model 3
reg testscr str el_pct expn_stu	//Model 3
est store model3

// 4. Summarise the coefficients and standard errors
est table model1 model2 model3, se title("Test scores")
* The best way to summarise the outputs in a way that makes them easily comparable is to tabulate the estimates.

// 5. Test hypothesis
test _b[str]=_b[expn_stu]=0
* or -test str expn_stu-
* Both methods produce the same result, which is that
	* the null hypothesis of both coefficients being zero is rejected,
	* i.e. at least one of the two is significantly different from zero.
